   USGS Hurricane Mitch Program Projects

   GIS Products
   Project Chief:  Paul Hearn
   Phone:703-648-6287
   Email:phearn@usgs.gov
   Project Summary
   GIS Image

   GIS technology offers powerful tools to compile and analyze information
   needed by municipal and national agencies for disaster mitigation,
   preparedness, and response. GIS is not widely used in Central America,
   however, due to the lack of digital maps, baseline data, data on
   hazards, lack of GIS hardware/software, and basic knowledge of GIS
   principles.
   Objectives
     * In coordination with USAID Missions, counterpart agencies, and
       municipal officials, the project will develop 1:50,000 scale GIS's
       for approximately 70 priority municipal areas in Honduras (40
       sites), Nicaragua (16 sites), El Salvador (7 sites) and Guatemala
       (7 sites). These GIS's will integrate digital base maps, aerial
       photography, maps of flood and landslide risk, and other
       information needed for disaster mitigation and response. GIS's will
       be delivered as ArcView and ArcExplorer projects on CD-ROM and also
       as paper maps.
     * The project will develop Disaster Management GIS's with counterpart
       agencies in Honduras, Nicaragua, El Salvador, and Guatemala at
       medium map scale (~1:250,000) for use as a planning tool by
       National Civil Defense agencies.
     * The project will work with counterpart agencies in Central America
       and NOAA to develop integrated GIS databases to support physical
       and biological assessments of shrimp-breeding areas in the Gulf of
       Fonseca, and coral reefs and nearshore ecosystems in the vicinity
       of the Bay Islands.
     * The project will conduct workshops to enure that sufficient
       in-country expertise with GIS exists so that municipalities and
       National Civil Defense agencies can use and continue to build the
       GIS products provided to them.

   Approach
   The USGS is already working with USAID Missions in Central America to
   facilitate the availability of digital and paper maps, acquire
   post-Mitch Aerial and Satellite Imagery, create maps of areas at risk
   from future flooding and landslides, and to provide hardware, software,
   and training to build local capacity in GIS. The GIS project will build
   upon these ongoing activites by developing
    a. simple, low-cost GIS products to assist priority municipalities in
       disaster mitigation, response, and planning
    b. national disaster management GIS's for use by Civil Defense
       Agencies in each country
    c. municipal disaster GIS's for use by municipalities and local or
       regional institutions
    d. GIS products to integrate biological assessments in the Gulf of
       Fonseca and Bay Islands.

   The project will also organize workshops and training to enhance the
   ability of specialists from municipalities and counterpart agencies to
   acquire and analyze simple geospatial data.
   The project will work with national counterpart agencies and selected
   priority municipalities in Honduras, Nicaragua, Guatemala, and El
   Salvador. Contacts will be with counterpart staff in federal agencies,
   USAID-designated NGO's, and also with engineers and other municipal
   officials in priority municipalities.
   Cooperating Agencies
     * Honduras: UNITEC, IGN, COPECO, SERNA, FUNDEMUN
     * Nicaragua: INETER, Civil Defense Committee, MAGFOR
     * El Salvador: IGN, COEN
     * Guatemala: IGN, CONRED,Universidad del Valle

   Source Data
   Local organization in the four countries, the EROS Data Center, the
   National Mapping Division, and the Eastern Earth Surface Processes Team
   of the Geologic Division in Reston VA.
   Products
   GIS data and custom applications
   The Municipal GIS is based on the compilation of several layers of
   information for an area of at least ten kilometers by ten kilometers
   around the town center of each municipality. For larger cities, the
   area might be larger or include additional data outside the main study
   area depending on the relevance and availability of the information.
   Each municipality will receive a dataset, a data viewer and a
   customized GIS application for updating and adding additional data.
